<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-417-078  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 417 078.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 10 1989 v6 n27 p14(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>First 100M-byte, 3.5-inch laptop disk expected to be shipped thismonth. (Areal Technology Inc.'s BP-100) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Areal Technology Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Areal Technology BP-100 (Disk drive) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Laptop computers3.5&quot; DiskDisk DrivesProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Areal Technology Inc. plans to ship to laptop-computer manufacturers thismonth the first single-platter, 100M-byte, 3-1/2-inch hard-disk drive.andM;Geared toward the laptop market, the new BP-100 drive features an AT buscontroller, uses only 1 watt of power and weighs 9 ounces.andM;The high density of the disk is achieved through the use of a glass platterinstead of the traditional aluminum platters, which average 25M bytes per3-1/2-inch platter.andM;Other features include a 7.5M-bps data-transfer rate and a 29 milliseconddata-access rate.andM;The glass platter reduces the flying height of the heads to less than 3microinches from the disk, resulting in greater linear bit densities,according to Jack Swartz, president of the San Jose, Calif., firm.andM;Areal also abandoned traditional hard-disk materials when designing thehead-disk assembly enclosure, which is made of less expensive, lighterthermoplastics instead of metal.andM;Areal first announced its glass platter last fall and scheduled it forshipment last January, but development delays have moved the shipment ofevaluation units to July, with production scheduled for August, Swartzexplained.andP;  Pricing has not been set.andM;Areal Technology can be contacted at (408) 954-0360.andO;</TEXT></DOC>